    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-05-27T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-05-27T03:00:00-05:00" n="548"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d548">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.1111 <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1"
                        >Baker, Charles</persName>/101: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1"
                            type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-05-27T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >May 27, 1932—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 27—10:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>574. Legation’s 567, May 25, 7 p.m.<note n="58" xml:id="d548fn58">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>[1.] Following from American Consul General at Hankow, <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“May 26, noon. My May 25, 5 p.m. <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_AGF1"
                                >Andrew</persName> has paid over to <persName
                                corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s captors $34,000 and
                            obtained their receipt for 416 tons of wheat. After the Communists had
                            received this payment in full for <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1"
                                >Baker</persName>’s release, one faction refused to release
                                <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName> without
                            receiving further payment. Present status of the matter is that
                            Communists have offered to release <persName
                                corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName> and take two Chinese
                            hostages in his stead provided <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_AGF1"
                                >Andrew</persName> will agree to deliver merchandise totaling about
                            $15,000 in value. <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_AGF1"
                                >Andrew</persName> is negotiating with them on this point. <persName
                                corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName> is to be released
                            before any further deliveries are made but agreement for further
                            deliveries must be made before release,”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p rend="flushleft">and</p>
                <p>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“May 26, 4 p.m. My May 26, noon. (1) Present situation is hopeful. Two
                            Chinese engineers have gone to Chuho to act as hostages. <persName
                                corresp="frus1932v03#p_AGF1">Andrew</persName>’s present problem now
                            is to agree on the amount and kind of merchandise to be sent to the
                            Communists for <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s
                            release.</p>
                        <p>(2) General representations demanding that the National Government obtain
                                <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s release
                            have resulted in instructions to the magistrates in the areas adjacent
                            to Kieli that they go in and obtain <persName
                                corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s release. The
                            Communists are aware of these instructions which have therefore greatly
                            increased the difficulties of <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_AGF1"
                                >Andrew</persName>’s negotiations. It is of the utmost importance
                            that no more representations be made to the Nanking Government at
                            present.</p>
                        <p>(3) I have great admiration for the patience and resourcefulness which
                                <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_AGF1">Andrew</persName> and his
                            Chinese associates are displaying in their efforts to obtain <persName
                                corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s release.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>American Consul General at Nanking directly informed by <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_AWA1">Adams</persName>.</p>
                <p>2. As previously stated Communists have excellent intelligence service and
                    Legation suggests that-above reports be treated as strictly confidential lest
                    publicity cause further miscarriage in plans to secure <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s release.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
